  "prompt": "How do I terminate the unresponsive application in Linux with the xkill command?",
  "response": "To terminate an unresponsive application in Linux using the xkill command, follow these steps:\n\n1. Open a terminal window\n\n2. Type the following command:\n```\nxkill\n```\n\n3. Your cursor will change to an X symbol\n\n4. Click on the window of the unresponsive application you want to close\n\n5. The application will be immediately terminated\n\nAlternative methods:\n\n1. To kill a specific process by its window ID:\n```\nxkill -id <window_id>\n```\n\n2. If xkill is not installed, first install it:\n```\n# For Ubuntu/Debian\nsudo apt-get install x11-utils\n\n# For Fedora\nsudo dnf install xorg-x11-utils\n\n# For Arch Linux\nsudo pacman -S xorg-xkill\n```\n\nTips:\n- Use with caution as it forcefully closes the application\n- Unsaved work may be lost\n- Always try to close applications normally first\n- Alternative command-line methods include 'killall' or 'pkill'",
